<font color="#FF0000">POLITICIANS AND PROTEST</font><br>
<tt>Sun Mar  9  9:37:23 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Politicians will almost always do things because of self interest. Their political survival is always given top consideration. I attribute this for their reluctance to involve us in warfare (ie J Winkler's refs to WWI &amp; II) , and for political expediency - how many of our allies in the Middle East are democracies?<br><br>
As a very politically unsophisticated 19 year old in 1968; I sat and watched as President Johnson announced that he would not seek reelection. I saw this as an abandonment of our so called mission - to say nothing of our war dead and wounded and those who still were fighting in Vietnam. The war was lost at that very moment. I'm positive that the South Vietnamese could see the writing on the wall.<br><br>
Also in 1968 we witnessed the invasion of Czechoslovakia. A clear cut invasion of a country whose PEOPLE SHOWED A WILLINGNESS TO STRUGGLE FOR DEMOCRACY. This was one of the saddest ironies of the 1960's, in my opinion. <br><br>
If we saw fit not to intervene when Communist troops from Eastern European countries and the Soviet Union  occupied Czechoslovakia, why did we insert ourselves in a CIVIL<br>
WAR such as Vietnam?<br><br>
Nixon soon entered the scene with his promise to end the war. It bothers me greatly to see that Henry Kissinger still has a widely sought after viewpoint.<br><br>
The war was viewed as being widely sanctioned by the American people in the 1972 election when Nixon defeated George McGovern. At that time great numbers of returning veterans were actively protesting the Vietnam War. Four years after Nixon made his first promises, the war still raged. The American people looked at McGovern as a defeatist - failing to realize that the war had been lost many years earlier.<br><br>

